  </math> cells
  is decreased in presence of the enzyme.
</p>

<h4 class="subsubsectionHead" id="311----generalization-to-other-gene-therapies"><span class="titlemark">3.1.1 </span>Generalization to other gene therapies</h4>
<p class="noindent">
  In this study, we focused on a permanent gene therapy. However, the perspective of
  gene therapies also concerns transitory gene therapies. For instance, in case of a bone
  fracture, it is possible to modify cells in such a way that they produce osteogenic
  growth factors and thus improve bone welding. This kind of therapy enables a more
  spatially targeted treatment than the injection of an exogenous protein <a href="#Xbaltzer2004regional">Baltzer and
Lieberman</a> (<a href="#Xbaltzer2004regional">2004</a>). In this case, the aim is not the invasion of a tissue by
  
